{
  "A salt is an ionic compound formed from:": "",
  "A metal and a nonmetal gas": "",
  "The cation of a base and the anion of an acid": "",
  "Two acids combining together": "",
  "Two bases combining together": "",
  "A salt is an ionic compound formed from the cation of the base and the anion of the acid during a neutralization reaction.": "",
  "HCl + NaOH produces the salt:": "",
  "NaOH (sodium hydroxide)": "",
  "HCl2 (hydrogen dichloride)": "",
  "NaCl (sodium chloride)": "",
  "NaH (sodium hydride)": "",
  "HCl + NaOH -> NaCl + H2O. The Na+ from the base and Cl- from the acid combine to form NaCl (sodium chloride).": "",
  "H2SO4 + 2KOH produces the salt:": "",
  "K2SO3 (potassium sulfite)": "",
  "KOH2 (potassium dihydroxide)": "",
  "KSO4 (potassium monosulfate)": "",
  "K2SO4 (potassium sulfate)": "",
  "H2SO4 + 2KOH -> K2SO4 + 2H2O. Two K+ ions from KOH pair with the SO4 2- ion from H2SO4 to form K2SO4.": "",
  "The salt from HNO3 + Ca(OH)2 is:": "",
  "CaN2O3 (calcium dinitrogen trioxide)": "",
  "CaNO3 (calcium mononitrate)": "",
  "Ca(NO3)2 (calcium nitrate)": "",
  "Ca2NO3 (dicalcium nitrate)": "",
  "2HNO3 + Ca(OH)2 -> Ca(NO3)2 + 2H2O. The Ca2+ from the base pairs with two NO3- from the acid to form Ca(NO3)2.": "",
  "To name a salt, combine:": "",
  "The metal name and the anion name from the acid": "",
  "Only the nonmetal name from the compound": "",
  "Only the metal name from the compound": "",
  "The acid name and the base name together": "",
  "To name a salt, use the cation (metal) name from the base and the anion name from the acid. For example, Na+ and Cl- give sodium chloride.": "",
  "The salt from H3PO4 + 3NaOH is:": "",
  "NaH3PO4 (sodium dihydrogen phosphate)": "",
  "Na3PO3 (sodium phosphite compound)": "",
  "Na3PO4 (sodium phosphate)": "",
  "NaPO4 (sodium monophosphate)": "",
  "H3PO4 + 3NaOH -> Na3PO4 + 3H2O. Three Na+ ions pair with the PO4 3- ion to form Na3PO4 (sodium phosphate).": "",
  "Salts formed from strong acid + strong base produce solutions that are:": "",
  "Neutral (pH approximately 7)": "",
  "Basic (pH greater than 10)": "",
  "Acidic (pH less than 4)": "",
  "Always colored in solution": "",
  "Salts from strong acid + strong base (like NaCl from HCl + NaOH) produce neutral solutions because neither ion hydrolyzes in water.": "",
  "The salt from HBr + LiOH is:": "",
  "LiBr (lithium bromide)": "",
  "HLi (hydrogen lithide)": "",
  "BrOH (bromine hydroxide)": "",
  "Li2Br (dilithium bromide)": "",
  "HBr + LiOH -> LiBr + H2O. The Li+ from the base and Br- from the acid combine to form LiBr (lithium bromide).": "",
  "The anion in the salt sodium sulfate (Na2SO4) came from the acid:": "",
  "HCl (hydrochloric acid)": "",
  "HNO3 (nitric acid)": "",
  "H2SO4 (sulfuric acid)": "",
  "H3PO4 (phosphoric acid)": "",
  "The sulfate ion (SO4 2-) in Na2SO4 comes from sulfuric acid (H2SO4). The cation Na+ comes from the base NaOH.": "",
  "When naming the salt from HCl, the anion name changes from chlorine to:": "",
  "Chlorate": "",
  "Chloride": "",
  "Chlorite": "",
  "Chlorous": "",
  "When naming salts from binary acids (like HCl), the anion gets the -ide suffix. Chlorine becomes chloride, so the salt is named with chloride (e.g., sodium chloride).": "",
  "What is a binary acid?": "",
  "An acid that contains hydrogen and one other element only": "",
  "An acid that contains two hydrogen atoms in its formula": "",
  "An acid that contains a polyatomic ion and hydrogen": "",
  "An acid that always has a charge of negative two": "",
  "A binary acid contains hydrogen and one other element (no oxygen). Examples include HCl (hydrochloric acid), HBr (hydrobromic acid), and HF (hydrofluoric acid).": "",
  "What is an oxyacid?": "",
  "An acid made of hydrogen, oxygen, and another element": "",
  "An acid that only contains oxygen and no hydrogen": "",
  "An acid with only two elements in its chemical formula": "",
  "An acid that dissolves metals but not other compounds": "",
  "An oxyacid contains hydrogen, oxygen, and at least one other element. Examples include H2SO4 (sulfuric acid), HNO3 (nitric acid), and H3PO4 (phosphoric acid).": "",
  "Define the term 'cation' as it relates to salt naming.": "",
  "A negatively charged ion that comes from the acid in a reaction": "",
  "A positively charged ion that typically comes from the base": "",
  "A neutral atom that does not carry any electrical charge at all": "",
  "A molecule that is formed during the process of neutralization": "",
  "A cation is a positively charged ion. In salt naming, the cation comes from the base (e.g., Na+ from NaOH) and is written first in the salt name.": "",
  "Define the term 'anion' as it relates to salt naming.": "",
  "A positively charged ion coming from the base in the reaction": "",
  "A neutral particle that does not take part in the reaction": "",
  "A negatively charged ion that comes from the acid in the reaction": "",
  "A polyatomic molecule formed only during synthesis reactions": "",
  "An anion is a negatively charged ion. In salt naming, the anion comes from the acid (e.g., Cl- from HCl) and is written second in the salt name.": "",
  "What does the suffix '-ate' indicate in a polyatomic ion name?": "",
  "The ion contains fewer oxygen atoms than the -ite form": "",
  "The ion contains more oxygen atoms than the -ite form": "",
  "The ion has no oxygen atoms in its chemical structure": "",
  "The ion is always paired with a monovalent metal cation": "",
  "The -ate suffix means the polyatomic ion has more oxygen atoms than the -ite form. For example, sulfate (SO4 2-) has more oxygen than sulfite (SO3 2-).": "",
  "What does the prefix 'hydro-' and suffix '-ic' indicate in acid naming?": "",
  "The acid is an oxyacid containing a polyatomic ion with oxygen": "",
  "The acid is a binary acid containing hydrogen and one other element": "",
  "The acid contains water molecules bonded to the central atom": "",
  "The acid produces hydroxide ions when dissolved in water": "",
  "The prefix 'hydro-' and suffix '-ic' indicate a binary acid. For example, HCl is hydrochloric acid (hydro- + chlor + -ic acid).": "",
  "What is a polyatomic ion?": "",
  "A single atom that has gained or lost one or more electrons": "",
  "A group of covalently bonded atoms that carries a net charge": "",
  "A neutral molecule that dissolves easily in water solutions": "",
  "A metal atom that has lost all its valence electron shells": "",
  "A polyatomic ion is a group of two or more covalently bonded atoms that together carry a net electrical charge. Examples include NO3- (nitrate), SO4 2- (sulfate), and PO4 3- (phosphate).": "",
  "What does the term 'dissociation' mean for salts in water?": "",
  "The salt molecules break apart into individual ions in solution": "",
  "The salt reacts with water to form a new acid and base pair": "",
  "The salt forms a precipitate that sinks to the bottom of water": "",
  "The salt evaporates from the water when heated to its boiling point": "",
  "Dissociation is the process by which an ionic compound (salt) separates into its individual ions when dissolved in water. For example, NaCl -> Na+ + Cl-.": "",
  "What is the naming rule for salts from oxyacids ending in '-ic acid'?": "",
  "The salt anion ends in '-ide' following the standard convention": "",
  "The salt anion ends in '-ate' following the standard convention": "",
  "The salt anion ends in '-ite' following the standard convention": "",
  "The salt anion ends in '-ous' following the standard convention": "",
  "When the parent acid ends in '-ic acid,' the corresponding salt anion ends in '-ate.' For example, sulfuric acid (H2SO4) produces sulfate salts.": "",
  "What is the naming rule for salts from oxyacids ending in '-ous acid'?": "",
  "When the parent acid ends in '-ous acid,' the corresponding salt anion ends in '-ite.' For example, sulfurous acid (H2SO3) produces sulfite salts.": "",
